'''He-He Er Xian''', translated as the '''Immortals of Harmony and Union''' and as the '''Two gods of Harmony and Union''', are two [[Taoism in China|Taoist]] [[Xian (Taoism)|immortals]]. They are popularly associated with happy marriages. He and He are typically depicted as boys holding a lotus flower ({{lang|zh|{{linktext|荷}}}}, ''hé'') and a box ({{lang|zh|{{linktext|盒}}}}, ''hé'').<ref>Welch, Patricia Bjaaland (2008). ''Chinese art: a guide to motifs and visual imagery.'' Tuttle Publishing. p. 270.</ref>

