{{Culture of the Federated States of Micronesia}}
[[Image:Pohnpei Kolonia Church.jpg|Catholic church in [[Kolonia]], [[Pohnpei]]|thumb|right]]

Several Protestant denominations, as well as the Roman Catholic Church, are active in every Micronesian state.<ref name=report>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2007/90145.htm |title=Micronesia, Federated States of: International Religious Freedom Report 2007 
|date=2007 |work=U.S. Department of State |accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> Most Protestant groups trace their roots to American Congregationalist missionaries.<ref name=report/> On the island of [[Kosrae]], the population is approximately 7,800; (95% Protestant). On [[Pohnpei]], the population of 35,000 is evenly divided between Protestants and Catholics (50% catholic & 50% Protestant). On [[Chuuk State|Chuuk]] and [[Yap]], (an estimated 60% Catholic & 40% Protestant). Religious groups with small followings include [[Baptists]], [[Assemblies of God]], [[Salvation Army]], [[Seventh-day Adventists]], [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (Mormons), and the [[Baha'i Faith]].  There is a small group of [[Buddhists]] on [[Pohnpei]], (0.7% Buddhist) (population as of 2010).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thearda.com/internationalData/Countries/Country_150_2.asp |publisher=The Association of Religion Data Archives |title=Religious Adherents, 2010 (World Christian Database) |accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> Attendance at religious services is generally high; [[church (building)|churches]] are well supported by their congregations and play a significant role in civil society.<ref name=report/> The [[Ahmadiyya|Ahmadiyya Muslims]] were registered in Kosrae in July 2015, despite strong public resistance against [[Islam]] in the country.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.marshallislandsjournal.com/Archive%207-10-15-page.html | title=Council bans Islam | publisher=Marshall Islands Journal | date=July 10, 2015 | accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref>

Most immigrants are Filipino Catholics who have joined local Catholic churches. The Filipino [[Iglesia Ni Cristo]] also has a church in Pohnpei. In the 1890s, on the island of Pohnpei, intermissionary conflicts and the conversion of clan leaders resulted in religious divisions along clan lines which persist today. Protestants are the majority on the western side of the island, while Catholics are the majority on the eastern side. Missionaries of many religious traditions are present and operate freely. The Constitution provides for [[freedom of religion]], and the Government generally respected this right in practice. The US government received no reports of societal abuses or discrimination based on religious belief or practice in 2007.<ref name=report/>

