The '''State Administration for Religious Affairs''' ('''SARA''') was a functioning department under the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] which oversaw religious affairs for the [[People's Republic of China]]. Originally created in 1951 as the Religious Affairs Bureau, SARA was closely connected with the [[United Front Work Department]] and charged with overseeing the operations of China's five officially sanctioned religious organizations: * [[Buddhist Association of China]] * [[Chinese Taoist Association]] * [[Islamic Association of China]] * [[Three-Self Patriotic Movement]] (Protestant) * [[Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association]] SARA was dissolved in 2018, placing all religious affairs directly under the United Front Work Department.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2138279/bigger-overseas-liaison-agency-fuels-fears-about|title=Fears about Chinese influence grow as more powers given to shadowy agency|last=Ng|first=Teddy|date=21 March 2018|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=24 March 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|last2=Lau|first2=Mimi|language=en}}</ref>
== History == The State Administration for Religious Affairs was established to exercise control over religious appointments, the selection of clergy, and the interpretation of religious doctrine. SARA was also meant to ensure that the registered religious organizations support and carry out the policy priorities of the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref>Congressional-Executive Commission on China, [http://www.cecc.gov/pages/virtualAcad/index.phpd?showsingle=136443 Top Leaders Praise the Work of China's "Patriotic Religious Organizations"] , 10 March 2010.</ref>
[[Ye Xiaowen]] directed the SARA from 1995 to 2009. During his tenure, he issued the [[State Religious Affairs Bureau Order No. 5]], which furthered state control over [[reincarnation]]s in [[Tibetan Buddhism]], and attempted to suppress [[Roman Catholicism in China|underground Catholics]] loyal to [[Holy See|Rome]] (which he considered "colonial") and not to the government-sanctioned [[Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=16351&size=A|title=CHINA Ye Xiaowen, party hound on Vatican and religions, is promoted|last=Cervellera|first=Bernardo|date=17 September 2009|website=www.asianews.it|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> After Ye was promoted to the Secretary of the CPC Committee at the [[Central Institute of Socialism]], the former Deputy Director {{ill |Wang Zuoan|zh|王作安}} was promoted to Director.<ref name="mingpao1">[http://news.sina.com.hk/cgi-bin/nw/show.cgi/94/1/1/1268390/1.html 宗教局長換人 專家指政策不變] (New Chairman for SARA, Experts Says Policy Has Not Changed), [[Ming Pao]], 18 September 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1056944.shtml?mc_cid=d34d47c815&mc_eid=1f9d28130a |publisher=''[[Global Times]]'' |title=Party members told to give up religion for Party unity or face punishment |first=Caiyu |last=Liu |date=July 18, 2017 |quote=[...] Wang Zuoan, director of the State Administration for Religious Affairs (SARA) wrote in an article released in the Qiushi Journal on Saturday, the flagship magazine of the CPC Central Committee.}}</ref> Under the [[Xi Jinping]] administration, it was announced in 2018 that SARA was being dissolved and its functions would be collapsed into the United Front Work Department.<ref name=":0" />
